<p><b>Mode</b> (from Latin <i>modus</i>, "measure, standard, manner, way") is a term from <a href="/wiki/Western_music" title="Western music">Western music</a> theory having three senses (Powers, 2001):</p>
<ol>
<li>the rhythmic relationship between long and short values in the late medieval period;</li>
<li>in early medieval theory, <a href="/wiki/Interval_(music)" title="Interval (music)">interval</a>;</li>
<li>most commonly, a concept involving <a href="/wiki/Musical_scale" title="Musical scale">scale</a> and melody type.</li>
</ol>
<p>In addition, from the end of the eighteenth century, the term began to be used in <a href="/wiki/Ethnomusicology" title="Ethnomusicology">ethnomusicological</a> contexts to describe pitch structures in non-European musical cultures, sometimes with doubtful compatibility (Powers 2001, §V,1).</p>
<p>This article addresses the scale-like meaning.</p>
